2.2 Wave function

Wave function takes the a single node data as input, and transform the data to N complete sinusoidal cycles. Below are some examples of using Wave function on data of a single node.

  • Notes:
    • Wave has two arguement:
      • node_data: Input one column at a time (here is 600x1 matrix)
      • register: set to 0 if want the result to be the original curves; set to 1 if want the result curves to center around 0

The following 2 plots are generated by Wave functions on the raw data of node 1 (before smoothing)

# extract periodic curves from a single node (before smoothing)
node1 = Wave(data_15may2020[,1], register=0)
ggplot(node1, aes(time, y_value,group=cycle, colour=cycle)) + geom_line() + theme(legend.position="top")

node1 = Wave(data_15may2020[,1], register=1)
ggplot(node1, aes(time, y_value,group=cycle, colour=cycle)) + geom_line() + theme(legend.position="top")

The following 2 plots are generated by Wave functions on the transformed data of node 1 (after smoothing) In the examples below, another function, fourier_smooth is called first to smooth the raw data using fourier basis functions.

  • Notes:
    • fourier_smooth has four arguments:
      • data_15may2020: Input data matrix, which should contains the entire data set, but we can use other arguments to select only subsets or Region of interest of the data for analysis
      • time_subset: specify a subset of time or all for analysis
      • node_subset: specify a subset of node or all for analysis
      • k: Specify the nummber of fourier basis functions to be used in the smoothing process
# extract periodic curves from a single node (after smoothing)
result_obj <- fourier_smooth(data_15may2020, time_subset=c(1:600), node_subset=c(1), k=32)
node1_smoothed = eval.fd(c(1:600),result_obj$fd)
node1_smoothed_extraced = Wave(node1_smoothed, register=0)
ggplot(node1_smoothed_extraced, aes(time, y_value,group=cycle, colour=cycle)) + geom_line() + theme(legend.position="top")

node1_smoothed_extraced = Wave(node1_smoothed, register=1)
ggplot(node1_smoothed_extraced, aes(time, y_value,group=cycle, colour=cycle)) + geom_line() + theme(legend.position="top")

2.3 fPCA.nodes function

fPCA.nodes function takes input data in matrix form (N rows x N columns), and transform the data to N complete sinusoidal cycles there has to be more than one column, otherwise PCA wont make sense. Below are some examples of using Wave function on data of a single node.

  • Notes:
    • fPCA.nodes has four arguements: data_mat, k, nharm, plt
      • data_mat: data in matrix form (N rows x N columns). Better just use the entire dataset here
      • k: set to 0 if want the result to be the original curves; set to 1 if want the result curves to center around 0
      • nharm:
      • plt:
# fPCA on raw data
rotpcalist = fPCA.nodes(data_15may2020, k=11, nharm=2, plt=1)
